const PHASE_MESSAGING = {
  name:"Phase 7 · Messaging & Async",id:"msg",icon:"📨",phase:"Messaging",color:"#7c3aed",
  sizes:["small","medium","large","hyper"],
  short:"Sync → job queue → message broker → event streaming — the architecture of decoupled, resilient systems",
  
  // ─── NEW SCHEMA KEY: conceptual primer for the phase ───
  primer:"Imagine a restaurant. In a synchronous architecture, the waiter takes your order, walks to the kitchen, stands there watching the chef cook, waits for the plate, then walks back to you — one customer at a time. In an asynchronous architecture, the waiter writes the order on a ticket, clips it to a rail, and immediately goes to serve the next table. The kitchen picks tickets off the rail at its own pace. The ticket rail is a message queue. This tiny mental model explains everything about messaging: decoupling (the waiter doesn't need to know which chef cooks the meal), load leveling (the rail absorbs a rush of orders without the kitchen falling behind), retry (if a chef drops a plate, the ticket is still on the rail — cook it again), and independent scaling (add more chefs without changing anything about the waiters). Every concept in this phase is a refinement of that restaurant ticket rail.",

  detail:{
    what:"Messaging is infrastructure for asynchronous communication between components of your system. The core contract: a producer drops a message (a unit of work or an event) into a queue, topic, or stream, and a consumer picks it up later — milliseconds, seconds, or even hours later. Producer and consumer don't have to be online at the same time, don't need to know about each other's existence, and scale completely independently. This decoupling is the single most powerful tool for building resilient, scalable systems — and the single largest source of new complexity when introduced. The messaging landscape spans a wide spectrum: (1) Background job queues (Sidekiq, Celery, Bull/BullMQ): the simplest form — your application enqueues a job into a Redis-backed queue, and a worker process in the same codebase picks it up. The job and the app share the same code, the same deploy, and usually the same language. Think: 'send this email,' 'resize this image,' 'generate this PDF.' (2) Message queues (SQS, RabbitMQ, Azure Service Bus): dedicated infrastructure that sits between services. The producer and consumer are separate applications. Messages are delivered at-least-once, meaning the consumer may receive the same message twice (network ack lost, consumer crashed after processing but before acknowledging). The queue guarantees delivery but not exactly-once processing — that's your job. Think: 'process this payment,' 'update this inventory,' 'notify this user.' (3) Event streaming platforms (Kafka, Kinesis, Pulsar, Redpanda): a durable, ordered, replayable log. Unlike a queue where messages disappear after consumption, a stream retains events for a configurable period (hours to forever). Multiple independent consumer groups can each read the entire stream at their own pace. This enables event sourcing, auditing, stream processing, and the ability to 'replay history' — rebuild a search index from scratch by re-reading all events. Think: 'every trip event at Uber,' 'every click on LinkedIn,' 'every trade on a stock exchange.' The right choice depends on your coupling needs, throughput, ordering requirements, and whether you need replay. Most systems evolve through all three tiers as they grow.",
    
    why:"Synchronous request-response is the default — and it's brittle by nature. Consider a checkout flow that synchronously calls 5 downstream services: payment processing (200ms), inventory update (50ms), email confirmation (300ms), analytics tracking (100ms), and fraud scoring (150ms). Total: 800ms if everything works. But if the email service is slow (2-second spike), your checkout takes 2.5 seconds. If the analytics service is down, your checkout returns a 500 error — even though the payment and inventory were the only critical parts. The user's purchase fails because a logging system hiccupped. Async messaging breaks this fragile chain. The checkout endpoint does only the critical synchronous work (charge card, reserve inventory — 250ms), then drops messages onto a queue for everything else (send email, track analytics, score fraud). The user gets their confirmation in 250ms. The email sends 2 seconds later. If analytics is down, the message sits in the queue until analytics recovers — no data lost, no user impact. This pattern — 'do the minimum synchronously, defer everything else' — is the foundation of every highly available system. But the benefits come with real costs that must be designed for explicitly: (1) Eventual consistency: the email hasn't sent yet when the user sees their confirmation page. If they check their inbox immediately, it's empty. Your UX must account for this ('Confirmation email will arrive within a few minutes'). (2) Idempotency: at-least-once delivery means your consumer might process the same message twice. If 'charge the credit card' runs twice, you've double-charged the customer. Every consumer must be designed to handle duplicates safely. (3) Ordering: messages may arrive out of order across partitions. If 'create user' and 'delete user' arrive in reverse order, you've resurrected a deleted user. Ordering guarantees cost throughput — design per use case. (4) Observability: a synchronous error shows up immediately in the API response. An async failure is silent — the message sits in a dead-letter queue and nobody notices for days unless you've built monitoring. Messaging is not a 'just add a queue' decision. It's an architectural commitment to a new programming model with new failure modes.",
    
    numbers:"The rule of thumb for when to go async: anything that takes >200ms in the user-facing request path AND doesn't need a synchronous result should be offloaded to a queue. Concrete examples: sending email (100–500ms, async always), resizing images (500ms–5s, async always), generating PDFs (1–10s, async always), updating a search index (variable, async always), sending push notifications (variable, async always), processing payments (200ms — async only if you can show 'processing' state to the user). Throughput by technology: SQS ~3,000 messages/sec per queue (can run multiple queues in parallel, effectively unlimited), RabbitMQ ~50,000 messages/sec per node with durable queues (higher with transient), Kafka 100,000–10,000,000 messages/sec per cluster depending on partition count and message size, Redpanda comparable to Kafka but with lower tail latency. Latency by technology: Sidekiq/Celery/Bull enqueue ~1ms, pickup ~2–10ms (limited by poll interval). SQS: 5–50ms end-to-end typical (long polling recommended, adds up to 20s wait on empty queue). RabbitMQ: 1–10ms end-to-end (push-based, very low latency). Kafka: <10ms producer-to-consumer at low volume, 30–100ms at scale (batch producer, consumer poll interval). Critical metric to monitor: consumer lag — the age of the oldest unprocessed message. If lag is growing, your consumers can't keep up with the production rate. This is a capacity problem, not a queue problem — add more consumer instances or optimize processing time. Alert when lag exceeds 2× your acceptable processing delay."
  },
  
  tradeoffs:[
    {axis:"Simplicity vs Decoupling",left:"Sync: simple mental model, easy to debug (one stack trace), but producer and consumer are coupled — a failure in either breaks both",right:"Async: decoupled, resilient, independently scalable — but harder to reason about, debug, and monitor. New failure modes (message loss, duplication, ordering)",pos:0.5},
    {axis:"Ordering vs Throughput",left:"Strict global ordering: every message processed in exactly the order produced — limits you to a single consumer (serial processing), throughput capped at one machine's speed",right:"Unordered / partition-ordered: messages can be processed in parallel across many consumers — 100× throughput, but you must handle out-of-order delivery in application logic",pos:0.5},
    // ─── NEW TRADEOFF ───
    {axis:"Delivery guarantee vs Performance",left:"Exactly-once (transactional outbox + idempotent consumers): correctest, but adds DB transaction per message and dedup check per consume — 2–5× slower",right:"At-most-once (fire and forget): fastest, but messages can be lost on crash — acceptable only for non-critical telemetry",pos:0.5}
  ],
  
  pitfalls:[
    {name:"Non-idempotent consumers — the #1 messaging bug",desc:"At-least-once delivery is the default for every production messaging system (SQS, RabbitMQ, Kafka). This means your consumer WILL receive the same message more than once — it's not a rare edge case, it's a normal operating condition (network blip loses the ack, consumer crashes after processing but before committing the offset, message visibility timeout expires during a slow GC pause). If your consumer charges a credit card on each message, duplicates = double charges. If it inserts a row, duplicates = duplicate records. The fix: make every consumer idempotent. Techniques: (1) Idempotency key — every message carries a unique ID (UUID). Consumer checks a 'processed_messages' table before acting. If the ID exists, skip. Use Redis SET NX with a 24-hour TTL for fast dedup. (2) Upsert instead of insert — use INSERT ... ON CONFLICT DO UPDATE so re-processing overwrites instead of duplicating. (3) Optimistic locking — include a version number in the message. Consumer only applies if current version matches. (4) For Kafka specifically: enable idempotent producer (enable.idempotence=true) + transactional consumer (isolation.level=read_committed) for exactly-once semantics within Kafka."},
    
    {name:"Dead-letter queue (DLQ) ignored — silent data loss",desc:"When a consumer fails to process a message after N retries (typically 3–5), the messaging system routes it to a Dead Letter Queue — a holding pen for poison pills. This is correct behavior: it prevents one bad message from blocking the entire queue. But here's what happens at most companies: nobody monitors the DLQ. Months later, someone discovers 100K messages in it — each representing a real user action that was never completed: an email never sent, an order never confirmed, a webhook never delivered. The DLQ is not a trash can — it's an emergency room waiting area. Fix: (1) Alert on DLQ depth > 0 immediately (PagerDuty, Slack). (2) Build a DLQ viewer UI that shows message content, failure reason, and retry count. (3) Build a 'replay' mechanism that re-drives DLQ messages back to the main queue after the bug is fixed (SQS has built-in DLQ redrive). (4) Classify DLQ messages: 'poison pill' (malformed, will never succeed — archive and alert), 'transient failure' (downstream was down — auto-retry after backoff), 'bug' (code error — fix code, then replay)."},
    
    {name:"Tight coupling via message schema — invisible API contract",desc:"Producer v2 adds a required 'priority' field to the message payload. Old consumers (still running v1) receive this message and fail to parse it — they crash or silently drop the message. You've just broken your consumers with a 'backward-incompatible schema change' — the same problem as breaking a REST API, except harder to detect because there's no HTTP 400 response to notice. The message schema IS an API contract, and it needs the same discipline: (1) Use a schema registry (Confluent Schema Registry for Kafka/Avro, Buf for Protobuf, AWS Glue Schema Registry). The registry enforces compatibility rules — it will reject a new schema version that breaks backward compatibility. (2) Schema evolution rules: new fields must have defaults (so old consumers ignore them), required fields can never be removed, field types can't change. (3) Use Avro or Protobuf instead of raw JSON — both have built-in schema evolution and are 5–10× smaller on the wire. (4) Version your message types explicitly: 'UserCreatedV2' rather than silently changing 'UserCreated.'"},
    
    {name:"Unbounded retry storms — the queue that ate itself",desc:"Consumer fails → message returns to queue → consumer picks it up → fails again → back to queue → repeat forever. Each failed attempt takes resources (CPU, DB connections, network) and the message never makes progress. With thousands of such messages, your entire consumer fleet is busy retrying doomed messages while new legitimate messages pile up. This is a retry storm and it's indistinguishable from a DDoS on your own consumers. Fix: (1) Set a max retry count (3–5 is typical). After max retries, route to DLQ — don't put it back in the main queue. (2) Use exponential backoff between retries (1s, 4s, 16s, 64s) so transient failures have time to resolve. (3) Add jitter to the backoff (random 0–100% of the delay) so multiple failed messages don't all retry simultaneously. (4) Distinguish retriable errors (timeout, 503, connection refused — retry with backoff) from permanent errors (400 Bad Request, schema validation failure, business rule violation — send directly to DLQ, no retry). SQS handles this with 'maxReceiveCount' on the redrive policy. Kafka requires application-level retry logic — use Spring Kafka's RetryTopic or a custom error handler."},
    
    // ─── NEW PITFALL ───
    {name:"Queue as database — the durability illusion",desc:"SQS retains messages for 14 days max. RabbitMQ can lose messages if the broker crashes without durable queues and persistent messages both enabled (they're separate settings — a common gotcha). Kafka retains for the configured retention period (default 7 days). None of these are databases. If you need to query historical messages, audit who sent what, or guarantee permanent retention, the queue is the wrong place. Pattern: use the transactional outbox — write the event to an 'outbox' table in your database (same transaction as the business data), then a separate process (Debezium CDC, polling publisher) reads the outbox and publishes to the queue. Now your database is the source of truth for the event, and the queue is just a transport mechanism. If the queue loses the message, the outbox still has it and can republish."}
  ],
  
  examples:[
    {name:"Stripe's idempotency keys + webhook queue — the gold standard",desc:"Stripe's webhook system is a masterclass in async design. When an event occurs (payment succeeded, subscription canceled), Stripe enqueues a webhook delivery. The delivery includes an idempotency key unique to that event. Stripe retries failed deliveries with exponential backoff for up to 3 days (intervals: 1 min, 5 min, 30 min, 2 hrs, 5 hrs, 10 hrs, 24 hrs). Each retry includes the same idempotency key. Stripe's documentation explicitly states: 'Your webhook handler must be idempotent. We may send the same event more than once.' They don't pretend to offer exactly-once delivery — they design the entire system around at-least-once and make idempotency the consumer's responsibility. This is honest, robust engineering. The lesson: don't fight the fundamental nature of distributed messaging (duplicates happen). Embrace it, document it, and make your consumers handle it."},
    
    {name:"LinkedIn Kafka origin — the event log that changed the industry",desc:"In 2010, LinkedIn's activity tracking system (page views, clicks, connection requests) needed to fan out to many downstream consumers: search indexing, recommendation engine, analytics, fraud detection, ad targeting. With point-to-point queues (ActiveMQ at the time), adding a new consumer meant wiring a new queue, duplicating data, and managing another delivery pipeline — O(N²) complexity for N producers and M consumers. Jay Kreps and team built Kafka as a distributed, durable, replayable log: producers write events to topics, and any number of consumers read independently from any position in the log. Adding a new consumer is zero-cost — just start reading from the beginning. Kafka now ingests trillions of events/day at LinkedIn. It spawned an entire ecosystem: Kafka Streams for processing, Kafka Connect for integration, KSQL for stream SQL, and the Confluent Platform. The lesson: when you need multiple independent consumers reading the same data, a durable log beats a queue every time. The log is the fundamental data structure of event-driven architecture."},
    
    // ─── NEW EXAMPLE ───
    {name:"Shopify's billion-job-per-day Sidekiq — simple tools at remarkable scale",desc:"Shopify processes over 1 billion background jobs per day using Sidekiq (Ruby) backed by Redis. Jobs include: processing payments, sending emails, syncing inventory, calculating taxes, and generating invoices. They didn't reach for Kafka or a complex event streaming platform — Sidekiq, a simple Redis-backed job queue with ~10 lines to enqueue a job, handles it. The secret: they invested heavily in job reliability (idempotent jobs, DLQ monitoring, per-job timeouts, separate queues for different priority classes) rather than in exotic infrastructure. This demonstrates a critical principle: simple job queues scale much further than people think. The operational complexity of running Sidekiq + Redis is 1/10th of running Kafka. Don't bring Kafka to a Sidekiq problem."}
  ],
  
  // ─── NEW SCHEMA KEY: decision matrix for choosing the right tool ───
  decisionMatrix:[
    {scenario:"Send an email after user signs up",answer:"Background job (Sidekiq/Celery/Bull)",reasoning:"Same codebase, no cross-service communication needed, simple retry semantics. Adding SQS or Kafka here is over-engineering."},
    {scenario:"Process payments from checkout service to payment service",answer:"Message queue (SQS/RabbitMQ)",reasoning:"Cross-service, needs guaranteed delivery and DLQ for failed payments. Doesn't need replay or multiple consumers."},
    {scenario:"User activity events consumed by search, analytics, and recommendations",answer:"Event streaming (Kafka/Kinesis)",reasoning:"Same event consumed by 3+ independent systems. Durable log lets each consume at their own pace. Replay enables rebuilding any downstream."},
    {scenario:"Nightly batch of 10K report-generation tasks",answer:"Background job with separate queue",reasoning:"Same codebase, bursty, doesn't need cross-service communication. Use a dedicated queue (not your main one) so it doesn't starve interactive jobs."},
    {scenario:"Real-time fraud scoring during checkout",answer:"Synchronous call — NOT async",reasoning:"You need the result before completing checkout. Async would let the order through before fraud scoring completes. Use a circuit breaker with a fallback (allow + flag for manual review)."}
  ],

  // ─── NEW SCHEMA KEY: key formulas and mental math ───
  formulas:[
    {name:"Consumer count needed",expr:"consumers = (messages_per_sec × avg_processing_time_sec) / target_utilization",note:"Example: 1000 msg/s × 0.1s processing / 0.7 utilization = 143 consumers. Over-provision by 30% (target 70% utilization) to absorb spikes."},
    {name:"Queue depth alarm threshold",expr:"alarm_depth = production_rate × max_acceptable_delay",note:"If you produce 100 msg/s and tolerate 60s max delay: alarm at 6,000 messages. If the queue exceeds this, you need more consumers NOW."},
    {name:"Retry budget",expr:"total_retries_per_hour = message_rate × failure_rate × avg_retries_before_DLQ",note:"At 10K msg/hr with 1% failure and 3 retries each: 300 retries/hr. If failures spike to 10%: 3,000 retries/hr — this can overwhelm consumers if not throttled."}
  ],
  
  levelUp:[
    {from:"small",to:"medium",trigger:">1K background jobs/day or any job failure causing permanent data loss — you've outgrown in-process job queues",
     action:"Move to a dedicated, persistent message queue service. Choose AWS SQS if you're on AWS (fully managed, zero ops, $0.40/M requests, at-least-once delivery, built-in DLQ and redrive) or RabbitMQ if you need routing flexibility or are multi-cloud (supports topic/fanout/header exchanges, but requires you to run and monitor the broker). Implementation steps: (1) Define your message schema explicitly — even for V1, write it down in a shared doc or proto file. (2) Add an idempotency key to every message (UUID v4 generated by the producer). (3) Build the consumer with idempotency check first — before writing any business logic, check if this message ID was already processed (Redis SET NX with 24h TTL is the simplest approach). (4) Configure a DLQ with maxReceiveCount=3 (SQS) or x-dead-letter-routing-key (RabbitMQ). (5) Set up monitoring: alert on DLQ depth > 0, alert on queue depth exceeding 2× normal, dashboard showing message rate, consumer lag, and processing time p99. (6) Build a DLQ viewer (even a simple script that reads and displays DLQ messages) and a replay mechanism from day one — you will need both within the first month."},
    
    {from:"medium",to:"large",trigger:">100K messages/day or ordering required or fan-out to 3+ consumers needed — SQS can't efficiently serve multiple independent consumers from the same stream",
     action:"Introduce Apache Kafka (self-managed), AWS MSK (managed Kafka), or Confluent Cloud (fully managed Kafka with schema registry, connectors, and stream processing). Kafka is the right choice when: (A) multiple independent consumers need the same events (each consumer group reads the full topic independently), (B) you need ordering within a partition (all events for a given entity go to the same partition via a partition key), (C) you need replay (re-read events from any offset to rebuild a downstream system), or (D) throughput exceeds 50K msg/sec. Implementation steps: (1) Design your topic structure: one topic per event type (user-created, order-placed, payment-processed) — not one topic per service. (2) Choose partition key carefully — it determines ordering AND parallelism. Typically entity ID (user_id, order_id) so all events for one entity are ordered. Partition count = 2–3× your expected consumer count (you can add partitions later but can't reduce them). (3) Set up Confluent Schema Registry or AWS Glue Schema Registry with BACKWARD compatibility mode — this prevents breaking schema changes from being published. Use Avro or Protobuf, not JSON. (4) Implement consumer groups: each downstream team creates their own consumer group (search-indexer, analytics-pipeline, notification-sender) that independently tracks its position in the log. (5) Set retention to 7 days minimum (allows replaying a week of events to rebuild a corrupted downstream). For event sourcing, set retention to 'forever' (retention.ms=-1). (6) Monitor: consumer group lag (Burrow or Kafka's built-in lag reporting), under-replicated partitions, broker disk usage, and producer error rate. Alert on consumer lag growing for >5 minutes."},
    
    {from:"large",to:"hyper",trigger:">1M events/sec or event sourcing is a business requirement or global fan-out across datacenters is needed",
     action:"Scale Kafka to a multi-cluster, multi-datacenter event streaming platform. Implementation: (1) Run dedicated Kafka clusters per domain or region — don't put everything on one cluster (blast radius). Typical: 3–10 clusters. (2) Cross-datacenter replication with MirrorMaker 2 (MM2) or Confluent Cluster Linking — replicate critical topics between clusters in different regions for DR and local read access. MM2 is open-source but operationally complex; Cluster Linking (Confluent) is simpler but requires Confluent Platform ($$$). (3) Deploy a centralized Schema Registry with BACKWARD_TRANSITIVE compatibility (ensures any new schema is compatible with ALL previous versions, not just the immediate predecessor). (4) Introduce stream processing with Apache Flink for real-time transformations, aggregations, and enrichments. Flink provides exactly-once guarantees, event-time processing (handles late-arriving events correctly), and savepoints (snapshot processing state for upgrades). Alternatives: Kafka Streams (simpler, library not a cluster, but limited to Kafka-to-Kafka), Apache Spark Structured Streaming (good for batch-friendly stream processing, but higher latency than Flink). (5) Implement a self-service topic provisioning system: teams request a topic through an internal portal, which provisions it with standard partition count, replication factor, schema, retention, and ACLs. This prevents topic sprawl and enforces standards. (6) Build an event catalog — a searchable registry of all event types, their schemas, who produces them, and who consumes them. Spotify's Backstage or a custom portal works. Without this, at 500+ topics nobody knows what events exist."}
  ],
  
  // ─── NEW SCHEMA KEY: technology comparison table ───
  technologyComparison:[
    {name:"Sidekiq",type:"Background job queue",throughput:"~25K jobs/sec",latency:"~2ms pickup",durability:"Redis persistence (AOF/RDB) — survives restart but not Redis data loss",ordering:"FIFO per queue",replay:"No",multiConsumer:"No (single worker pool)",bestFor:"Ruby applications, simple async tasks, same-codebase producer/consumer",weaknesses:"Redis is the single point of failure. No cross-service communication. Ruby-only (though Faktory is the polyglot equivalent by the same author)."},
    {name:"Celery",type:"Background job queue",throughput:"~10K tasks/sec",latency:"~5–20ms pickup",durability:"Depends on broker (Redis or RabbitMQ)",ordering:"No global ordering",replay:"No",multiConsumer:"No",bestFor:"Python applications, same-codebase async tasks, periodic/scheduled jobs (Celery Beat)",weaknesses:"Notoriously complex configuration. Memory leaks in long-running workers. Python-only. Monitoring requires Flower (separate tool)."},
    {name:"Bull/BullMQ",type:"Background job queue",throughput:"~15K jobs/sec",latency:"~5ms pickup",durability:"Redis-backed",ordering:"FIFO per queue, priority queues supported",replay:"No, but supports job events and history",multiConsumer:"No",bestFor:"Node.js applications, job scheduling, rate-limited processing",weaknesses:"Redis dependency. Node.js-only. Less battle-tested at extreme scale than Sidekiq."},
    {name:"AWS SQS",type:"Message queue",throughput:"~3K msg/sec/queue standard, ~30K with batching, unlimited with multiple queues",latency:"5–50ms",durability:"Replicated across 3 AZs, 4-day default retention (max 14 days)",ordering:"FIFO queues available (300 msg/sec/group, 3K with batching) or standard (best-effort, much higher throughput)",replay:"No — once consumed and deleted, gone forever",multiConsumer:"No (single consumer per message — each message delivered to one consumer)",bestFor:"Simple task queues, decoupling services on AWS, zero-ops messaging",weaknesses:"No replay. No multi-consumer fan-out (use SNS+SQS fan-out pattern for that). FIFO throughput is limited. No stream processing. AWS lock-in."},
    {name:"RabbitMQ",type:"Message broker",throughput:"~50K msg/sec per node",latency:"1–10ms",durability:"Durable queues + persistent messages survive broker restart. Quorum queues (v3.8+) replicate across nodes for HA.",ordering:"Per-queue FIFO",replay:"No (messages deleted after ack)",multiConsumer:"Fan-out via exchanges (topic, fanout, headers) — one message routed to multiple queues",bestFor:"Complex routing (send order events to both billing and shipping queues), RPC patterns, multi-cloud (no vendor lock-in), low-latency messaging",weaknesses:"Operational burden (you run the cluster). Messages lost if broker crashes without durable+persistent both set. Doesn't scale horizontally as easily as Kafka. No replay."},
    {name:"Apache Kafka",type:"Event streaming platform",throughput:"100K–10M msg/sec per cluster",latency:"<10ms at low volume, 30–100ms at scale",durability:"Replicated across brokers (replication factor 3 typical). Retention for days/weeks/forever.",ordering:"Per-partition ordering guaranteed (all events with same partition key arrive in order)",replay:"Yes — consumers can re-read from any offset (within retention window). This is Kafka's superpower.",multiConsumer:"Yes — unlimited independent consumer groups, each reading the full log at their own pace",bestFor:"High-throughput event streaming, event sourcing, multi-consumer fan-out, audit logs, stream processing",weaknesses:"Operational complexity is significant (ZooKeeper dependency removed in KRaft mode as of 3.3+, but cluster management is still complex). Partition count must be set at topic creation (can increase but not decrease). Consumer rebalancing can cause brief processing pauses. Expensive at small scale (minimum 3 brokers for production). Learning curve is steep."},
    {name:"Redpanda",type:"Event streaming platform (Kafka-compatible)",throughput:"Comparable to Kafka, lower tail latency",latency:"<10ms p99 (vs Kafka's sometimes spiky p99)",durability:"Same as Kafka (replication factor configurable)",ordering:"Same as Kafka",replay:"Yes (Kafka-compatible)",multiConsumer:"Yes (Kafka-compatible consumer groups)",bestFor:"Teams that want Kafka semantics without ZooKeeper/JVM complexity. Single binary, written in C++, lower resource consumption.",weaknesses:"Smaller community than Kafka. Fewer integrations (though Kafka API compatibility covers most). Newer, less battle-tested at extreme scale. Commercial features (tiered storage, RBAC) require Redpanda Enterprise."},
    {name:"AWS Kinesis",type:"Event streaming",throughput:"~1K records/sec per shard, scale by adding shards",latency:"~200ms end-to-end",durability:"24hr–365 day retention",ordering:"Per-shard",replay:"Yes (within retention)",multiConsumer:"Yes (multiple applications via enhanced fan-out)",bestFor:"AWS-native streaming. Simpler than Kafka for small-medium stream processing on AWS.",weaknesses:"Per-shard throughput limit (1 MB/s write, 2 MB/s read). Gets expensive at scale (more shards = more $$$). Fewer integrations than Kafka ecosystem. Resharding is slow. AWS lock-in."},
    {name:"Confluent Cloud",type:"Fully managed Kafka",throughput:"Same as Kafka (managed)",latency:"Same as Kafka",durability:"Managed by Confluent (multi-AZ)",ordering:"Same as Kafka",replay:"Yes",multiConsumer:"Yes",bestFor:"Teams that want Kafka without operating it. Includes Schema Registry, Connectors, ksqlDB, Stream Governance as managed services.",weaknesses:"Expensive ($1+ per CKU-hour, minimum ~$750/month for dedicated clusters). Vendor dependency on Confluent. Some Kafka features lag behind open-source releases."}
  ],
  
  sizes_cfg:{
    small:{range:"<1K async tasks/day, single service, single codebase",rec:"Use the background job library native to your framework: Sidekiq for Ruby (the gold standard — fast, reliable, excellent UI dashboard), Celery for Python (powerful but complex configuration — start with Redis broker, not RabbitMQ), Bull/BullMQ for Node.js (Redis-backed, priority queues, rate limiting built in), or Delayed::Job for Rails if you want DB-backed simplicity. All are backed by Redis (except Delayed::Job which uses your DB). Don't over-engineer with a separate message queue service — at this scale, the operational overhead of running RabbitMQ or reasoning about SQS message visibility timeouts is not worth it. The job runs in the same codebase, same deploy, same language. Keep it simple. Focus your effort on making jobs idempotent (check 'already processed?' before acting) and setting per-job timeouts (a hung job shouldn't block a worker forever).",tools:["Sidekiq","Celery","Bull/BullMQ","Delayed::Job"]},
    
    medium:{range:"1K–100K messages/day, 2+ services communicating, need guaranteed delivery",rec:"Graduate to a dedicated message queue. AWS SQS is the lowest-ops choice for teams on AWS: fully managed, pay-per-message ($0.40/million), automatic 3-AZ replication, built-in DLQ with configurable redrive policy, and you never have to SSH into a broker at 3am. Use SQS Standard (at-least-once, best-effort ordering, ~3K msg/sec) for most workloads; SQS FIFO (exactly-once processing within a message group, strict ordering, ~300 msg/sec per group) only when ordering is a hard requirement. For fan-out (one event → multiple queues), use SNS → SQS fan-out pattern: SNS topic publishes to multiple SQS queues, each consumed independently. Visibility timeout = max processing time × 2 (if your job takes 30s max, set visibility to 60s — otherwise the message becomes visible to another consumer while the first is still processing it, causing duplicates). If you're multi-cloud or need complex routing (e.g., 'route order events to both the billing queue and the shipping queue based on message attributes'), use RabbitMQ. Self-hosted on a 3-node cluster for quorum queues (HA). CloudAMQP is a managed option ($19/month for shared, $99+ for dedicated). Azure Service Bus and GCP Pub/Sub are the cloud-native equivalents for their respective platforms. Always configure a DLQ and monitor its depth — alert on depth > 0.",tools:["AWS SQS","SNS+SQS fan-out","RabbitMQ","Azure Service Bus","GCP Pub/Sub"]},
    
    large:{range:"100K–10M messages/day, 3+ consumers per event type, ordering required, replay needed",rec:"This is Kafka territory. You need Kafka (or a Kafka-compatible system) when: (A) the same event must be consumed by multiple independent systems (search, analytics, notifications all need 'order-placed' events), (B) you need to replay events to rebuild a downstream system (re-index all products in Elasticsearch by replaying from the beginning of the topic), (C) you need per-entity ordering (all events for order #12345 processed in sequence), or (D) throughput exceeds what SQS/RabbitMQ handle comfortably. Run Kafka on AWS MSK ($0.21–0.75/hr per broker) for managed operations, or Confluent Cloud ($750+/month) for fully managed with Schema Registry and connectors included. Self-managing Kafka is viable but budget 0.5–1 full-time engineer for cluster operations. Use KRaft mode (no ZooKeeper) for new deployments — simpler architecture, fewer moving parts. Minimum production setup: 3 brokers, replication factor 3, 2+ partitions per topic. At-least-once delivery + idempotent consumers = exactly-once application semantics. Schema Registry is non-negotiable at this scale: Confluent Schema Registry (open-source, Avro/Protobuf/JSON Schema) or AWS Glue Schema Registry (managed, integrates with MSK). Alternative: Apache Pulsar offers Kafka-like streaming with built-in multi-tenancy and geo-replication, but the ecosystem is smaller. Redpanda is Kafka-API-compatible with simpler operations (single C++ binary, no JVM, no ZooKeeper) — excellent choice if your team is smaller.",tools:["Apache Kafka","AWS MSK","Confluent Platform","Redpanda","Apache Pulsar"]},
    
    hyper:{range:">10M messages/day, global distribution, event sourcing, stream processing",rec:"Kafka at massive scale: 1M–10M events/sec per cluster, multiple clusters per domain or region. Multi-datacenter replication with MirrorMaker 2 (open-source, active-active or active-passive replication between Kafka clusters across regions) or Confluent Cluster Linking (simpler, but requires Confluent Platform). Schema Registry with BACKWARD_TRANSITIVE compatibility enforcement — every new schema version must be compatible with all prior versions, not just the last one. Event sourcing as the core data architecture: the Kafka log is the source of truth, and all databases/caches/indexes are materialized views derived from replaying the log. This gives you a complete audit trail, the ability to rebuild any downstream system, and temporal queries ('what did the order look like at 3pm yesterday?'). Stream processing with Apache Flink: real-time transformations, enrichment (join a click event with user profile data), windowed aggregations (count events per 5-minute window), and complex event processing (detect fraud patterns across event sequences). Flink provides exactly-once semantics, event-time processing, and savepoints for version upgrades. At this scale, consider building an internal 'event platform' team that owns the Kafka clusters, Schema Registry, Flink pipelines, and the event catalog (what events exist, who produces them, who consumes them). Teams self-service topics through an internal portal. Without governance, you end up with 2,000 topics, half undocumented, and nobody knows what 'user-events-v3-final-FINAL' contains.",tools:["Kafka (self-managed clusters)","Confluent Cloud","AWS Kinesis","Apache Flink","MirrorMaker 2","custom event platform"]}
  },
  
  children:[
    {name:"Async Pattern",id:"msg-pattern",icon:"🔄",phase:"Messaging",color:"#7c3aed",
     sizes:["small","medium","large","hyper"],
     short:"None → background jobs → MQ → event streaming — choose the lightest tool that meets your actual needs",
     
     // ─── NEW SCHEMA KEY on child ───
     primer:"The three async patterns form a maturity ladder, but 'maturity' doesn't mean 'better.' A Sidekiq background job is the right answer for 80% of async work, the same way a bicycle is the right vehicle for a trip to the corner store. Using Kafka for 'send a welcome email' is like taking a helicopter to the corner store — technically possible, expensive, and absurd. Match the tool to the job.",
     
     detail:{
       what:"The pattern by which work is deferred from the synchronous request path. Three tiers, each with distinct capabilities and costs: (1) Background jobs (Sidekiq, Celery, Bull/BullMQ, Delayed::Job): the simplest async pattern. Your application enqueues a job — a serialized function call with arguments — into a Redis-backed queue. A worker process (usually in the same codebase and deploy) picks it up and executes it. Jobs are transient: once processed, they're gone (no replay). Single consumer per job. Best for: work that lives in the same codebase, doesn't need cross-service communication, and doesn't need replay — sending emails, resizing images, generating PDFs, syncing external APIs. (2) Message queues (SQS, RabbitMQ, Azure Service Bus, GCP Pub/Sub): a dedicated service that sits between producer and consumer services. Messages are delivered at-least-once to a single consumer (or fan-out via exchanges/SNS). Messages disappear once acknowledged. The queue provides guaranteed delivery, dead-letter queues, and visibility timeouts — features that background jobs don't have natively. Best for: cross-service communication with reliable delivery — 'Checkout Service → Payment Service: process this payment,' 'Order Service → Warehouse Service: ship this order.' (3) Event streaming (Kafka, Kinesis, Pulsar, Redpanda): a durable, ordered, replayable log. Events persist for days, weeks, or forever. Multiple independent consumer groups each read the entire stream at their own pace. This is fundamentally different from a queue: events are not 'consumed' and destroyed — they're 'read' and retained. Best for: multi-consumer fan-out, event sourcing, audit trails, and building derived views (search index, analytics pipeline, recommendation engine) from a shared event stream.",
       
       why:"Each pattern fits a different need, and picking the wrong one costs you in either unnecessary complexity or missing capabilities. Background jobs (Sidekiq/Celery): operationally simplest — no external message broker to manage, same codebase, same deploy, familiar programming model. But: no cross-service communication, no fan-out, no replay. If you need any of these, you'll end up hacking around the limitation (shared Redis between services, polling a DB for new work) and building a worse version of a message queue. Message queues (SQS/RabbitMQ): add reliable cross-service delivery, DLQ, visibility timeouts, and routing. But: no replay (once consumed, the message is gone), no multi-consumer (each message goes to one consumer — fan-out requires SNS+SQS or exchange+binding patterns, which add complexity), and no ordering (SQS Standard is best-effort; FIFO queues are throughput-limited). If you need replay or many independent consumers, you'll build a worse Kafka. Event streaming (Kafka): adds durable replay, multi-consumer fan-out, per-partition ordering, and stream processing. But: 10× the operational complexity of SQS, 100× of Sidekiq. Running Kafka in production requires understanding brokers, partitions, consumer groups, rebalancing, retention, compaction, ISR (in-sync replicas), and schema evolution. If you don't need replay or multi-consumer, Kafka is overkill and the complexity will slow you down. The golden rule: use the lightest tool that meets your actual requirements. Don't pre-optimize for requirements you might have someday.",
       
       numbers:"Overhead by pattern — the real cost of each tier: Sidekiq: ~1ms to enqueue, ~2–10ms to pick up (Redis polling), operationally zero (it's a gem/library, not a service). Celery: ~3–10ms to enqueue (serialize + broker write), ~5–20ms to pick up, operationally light (Redis as broker) to moderate (RabbitMQ as broker). SQS: 5–50ms end-to-end (API call to AWS, long polling on consumer side), operationally zero (fully managed by AWS). RabbitMQ: 1–10ms end-to-end (push-based, very low latency), operationally moderate (you run the cluster, monitor disk space, handle upgrades). Kafka: <10ms producer-to-consumer at low volume, 30–100ms at high volume (batch producer, consumer poll interval), operationally heavy (minimum 3 brokers, monitoring ISR, partition balancing, retention management). Replay capability — the key differentiator: Sidekiq/Celery/Bull: none. SQS: none (once deleted, gone forever; DLQ redrive is the closest to replay). RabbitMQ: none (messages deleted after ack). Kafka/Kinesis/Pulsar: full replay within retention window — seek to any offset and re-read all events. Rule of thumb for offloading: if it takes >200ms and the user doesn't need a synchronous answer, make it async. Email (always), image resize (always), PDF generation (always), search indexing (always), notification push (always), payment processing (usually sync because user needs confirmation, but can be async with a 'processing' intermediate state)."
     },
     
     tradeoffs:[
       {axis:"Latency vs Resilience",left:"Sync: immediate result, but if downstream fails, caller fails too — the chain is as fragile as its weakest link",right:"Async: result comes later, but failures are retried automatically, spikes are absorbed by the queue, and the caller is isolated from downstream problems",pos:0.5},
       {axis:"Throughput vs Ordering",left:"Unordered processing (SQS Standard, Kafka multiple partitions with different keys): messages can be consumed in parallel across many workers — maximum throughput, minimum latency",right:"Ordered processing (SQS FIFO, Kafka single partition): messages for a given entity processed in sequence — prevents race conditions, but limits parallelism to one worker per ordering group",pos:0.5},
       // ─── NEW TRADEOFF ───
       {axis:"Operational simplicity vs Capability",left:"Sidekiq/Bull: zero new infrastructure, same deploy, same language — but limited to single service, single consumer, no replay",right:"Kafka: replay, multi-consumer, ordering, event sourcing — but 10× ops complexity, separate infrastructure, steep learning curve, minimum 3-node cluster",pos:0.5}
     ],
     
     pitfalls:[
       {name:"Using Kafka when SQS or even Sidekiq would do — the '100× overengineering' trap",desc:"You need to send a confirmation email after user signup. An engineer proposes Kafka because 'we'll need it eventually for analytics.' Now you're running a 3-broker Kafka cluster ($500+/month) with ZooKeeper, learning about consumer group rebalancing, and debugging offset commits — all to send an email. Sidekiq would have been 3 lines of code and zero new infrastructure. Kafka adds operational complexity that's justified only when you need its specific capabilities: replay, multi-consumer fan-out, high-throughput streaming, or per-partition ordering. At <10K messages/sec with a single consumer, SQS is simpler and cheaper. At <1K tasks/day within a single service, Sidekiq/Celery/Bull is the right answer. Ask: 'Do I need replay? Do I need multiple independent consumers reading the same events? Do I need >50K msg/sec?' If no to all three, you don't need Kafka yet."},
       
       {name:"Background job DB updates without idempotency — the silent double-count",desc:"A Sidekiq job increments a counter: `Analytics.increment(:page_views)`. The job runs, increments the counter, then crashes before the Redis ACK. Sidekiq retries the job. Counter is now incremented twice. At 1 million jobs/day with a 0.1% retry rate, you have 1,000 double-counted metrics per day — enough to corrupt your analytics. Fix: use idempotent operations. Instead of `increment(:page_views)`, use `set(:page_views, computed_value)` or `upsert(date: today, views: calculated_count)`. For operations that can't be made idempotent naturally, use a dedup key: the job carries a unique ID, and the consumer checks a Redis set (SADD returns 0 if already present) before acting."},
       
       {name:"Long-running jobs blocking workers — the queue starvation problem",desc:"A 5-minute PDF generation job ties up a worker. If you have 10 workers and 3 of them are generating PDFs, only 7 are available for everything else — and your 50ms email-sending jobs are waiting behind the PDFs. The queue backs up. Fix: (1) Use separate queues for different job priority classes: 'critical' (payment processing, 10 workers), 'default' (emails, notifications, 20 workers), 'low' (PDF generation, report building, 5 workers). Sidekiq, Celery, and Bull all support multiple named queues with configurable worker counts. (2) Set per-job timeouts: if a PDF job normally takes 2 minutes, set a 5-minute timeout — kill it if it exceeds that, send to DLQ for investigation, and prevent it from permanently consuming a worker. (3) For truly long-running work (>5 minutes), consider splitting into stages: 'prepare data' → 'render PDF' → 'upload to S3' → 'notify user,' each as a separate short job chained together."},
       
       // ─── NEW PITFALL ───
       {name:"Async makes debugging 10× harder — plan for observability from the start",desc:"Synchronous: request fails → stack trace shows exactly what went wrong → fix it. Async: request succeeds (200 OK, message enqueued) → message fails processing 30 seconds later in a different service → no one notices until the DLQ alert fires (if it fires) → the stack trace is in a different service's logs → correlating the original request to the failed processing requires a correlation ID that you hopefully included in the message. Without deliberate observability, async turns debugging from 'read the stack trace' into 'reconstruct what happened across multiple services by correlating timestamps in multiple log streams.' Fix: (1) Include a correlation_id (trace ID) in every message, propagated from the original HTTP request. (2) Use structured logging with the correlation_id in every log line — both producer and consumer. (3) Instrument message production and consumption with distributed tracing (OpenTelemetry supports messaging spans). (4) Build a message flow visualization: for a given correlation_id, show the path through all queues and services."}
     ],
     
     examples:[
       {name:"Shopify: billions of Sidekiq jobs per day — proof that simple scales",desc:"Shopify processes over 1 billion background jobs daily on Sidekiq + Redis. Not Kafka. Not a custom event streaming platform. Sidekiq — a Ruby library backed by Redis. They handle payment processing, email sending, inventory syncing, tax calculation, and more. The key to their scale isn't exotic infrastructure — it's disciplined job design: every job is idempotent, every job has a timeout, different priority classes use separate queues with dedicated worker pools, and they monitor job latency and failure rates per queue. The lesson: Sidekiq's operational simplicity (it's a gem, not a cluster) means they invest engineering time in business logic, not infrastructure operations. Kafka would have given them replay and multi-consumer — neither of which they needed for these workloads."},
       
       {name:"Uber's event sourcing on Kafka — every trip event, replayable forever",desc:"At Uber, every trip generates a sequence of events: ride requested, driver matched, driver en route, pickup, ride started, ride completed, fare calculated, payment processed. Each event goes to Kafka. Multiple independent consumer groups process these events: the pricing engine (calculates dynamic pricing from demand events), the analytics pipeline (builds trip dashboards), the fraud detection system (looks for suspicious patterns across events), the support tooling (shows the full trip timeline when a user complains), and the receipts system (generates the email receipt). Replay is critical: when Uber rebuilt their fraud detection model, they replayed 6 months of trip events through the new model to validate it before deploying. Without Kafka's replay capability, they would have had to wait months for enough new data to accumulate. The lesson: when multiple downstream systems independently consume the same events, and replay is valuable, Kafka's durable log model is transformative."},
       
       // ─── NEW EXAMPLE ───
       {name:"Stripe's webhook delivery system — at-least-once with grace",desc:"When an event occurs (payment_intent.succeeded, customer.subscription.deleted), Stripe enqueues a webhook delivery job. The system retries with exponential backoff (1 min, 5 min, 30 min, 2 hr, 5 hr, 10 hr, 24 hr — 7 attempts over ~3 days) until it receives an HTTP 2xx from the customer's endpoint. Each delivery includes the same event ID, allowing the customer's system to deduplicate. Stripe's internal architecture uses a job queue (not Kafka) for this — because each webhook delivery goes to one destination (single consumer) and doesn't need replay or fan-out. They explicitly chose the simplest tool that met the requirements. Stripe's documentation is a masterclass in teaching consumers about idempotency: 'Webhook endpoints might occasionally receive the same event more than once. We advise you to guard against duplicated event receipts by making your event processing idempotent.'"}
     ],
     
     sizes_cfg:{
       small:{range:"Cron jobs + inline async tasks — <1K tasks/day, single service",rec:"Use the background job library in your framework. Sidekiq (Ruby): the gold standard — fast (~25K jobs/sec), excellent web UI dashboard (real-time view of queues, retries, dead jobs), Redis-backed, built-in retry with exponential backoff. Celery (Python): powerful but complex — supports Redis or RabbitMQ as broker, has Celery Beat for periodic tasks, but configuration is notoriously tricky and memory leaks in long-running workers are common (use --max-tasks-per-child). Bull/BullMQ (Node.js): modern, well-designed — supports priority queues, rate limiting, delayed jobs, and repeatable jobs out of the box; BullMQ (v4+) is the rewrite with better TypeScript support. Delayed::Job (Rails): the simplest possible option — stores jobs in your database (no Redis needed), but slower and less featured than Sidekiq. Use it only if adding Redis is overkill for your single-digit-jobs-per-day workload. At this scale, don't introduce a separate message queue service. The complexity isn't worth it. Focus on making jobs idempotent and setting timeouts.",tools:["Sidekiq","Celery","Bull/BullMQ","Delayed::Job"]},
       
       medium:{range:"Dedicated message queue service — 1K–100K messages/day, cross-service communication",rec:"AWS SQS for zero-ops simplicity on AWS: fully managed, pay-per-request ($0.40/M for standard, $0.50/M for FIFO), built-in DLQ with configurable maxReceiveCount, long polling (reduces empty responses and cost), and message retention up to 14 days. Use SNS → SQS fan-out when one event needs to reach multiple queues (e.g., 'order-placed' goes to both the fulfillment queue and the analytics queue). For multi-cloud or complex routing: RabbitMQ with quorum queues (replicated across cluster nodes for HA). CloudAMQP ($19–499/month for managed) eliminates operational burden. GCP Pub/Sub is Google's equivalent (serverless, global, exactly-once delivery in order mode) and Azure Service Bus is Azure's (sessions for ordered processing, transactions for atomic multi-message operations). Set visibility timeout = max processing time × 2 (too short → duplicate processing; too long → slow retry on actual failure). Monitor DLQ depth (alert > 0), approximate age of oldest message (alert > 2× acceptable delay), and number of messages in flight (approaching the concurrency limit means you need more consumers).",tools:["AWS SQS","SNS+SQS fan-out","RabbitMQ","Azure Service Bus","GCP Pub/Sub"]},
       
       large:{range:"Message broker with guaranteed delivery — 100K–10M messages/day, ordering + replay + multi-consumer",rec:"Apache Kafka when you need replay, multi-consumer fan-out, per-entity ordering, or throughput >50K msg/sec. Run on AWS MSK ($0.21–0.75/broker-hr for provisioned, or MSK Serverless at $0.10/GB) for managed operations or Confluent Cloud ($750+/month for dedicated) for fully managed with Schema Registry, Connectors, ksqlDB included. Self-manage only if you have dedicated platform engineers — Kafka operations (broker rolling restarts, partition reassignment, ISR monitoring, retention tuning) require genuine expertise. Alternative: Redpanda — Kafka-API-compatible, single C++ binary (no JVM, no ZooKeeper), lower tail latency, simpler operations. Excellent for teams with <5 infrastructure engineers who want Kafka semantics without Kafka complexity. Apache Pulsar offers native multi-tenancy and built-in geo-replication — strong choice if you need these from day one. For all options: implement at-least-once delivery + idempotent consumers to achieve exactly-once application semantics. Use Confluent Schema Registry (open-source) or AWS Glue Schema Registry for message contract enforcement. Monitor consumer group lag obsessively — it's the primary indicator of consumer health.",tools:["Apache Kafka","AWS MSK","Confluent Platform","Redpanda","Apache Pulsar"]},
       
       hyper:{range:"Event streaming platform — >10M messages/day, event sourcing, global replication, stream processing",rec:"Kafka at massive scale: multiple clusters (3–10), each handling millions of events/sec. Multi-datacenter replication with MirrorMaker 2 (open-source active-active/active-passive cross-cluster replication) or Confluent Cluster Linking (simpler but Confluent-only). Schema Registry in BACKWARD_TRANSITIVE mode — no schema change can ever break any historical consumer. Event sourcing as the core data model: the Kafka log is the authoritative record of everything that happened; all databases, caches, and search indexes are materialized views derived by replaying events. This enables temporal queries ('what was the state at time T?'), audit trails, and the ability to rebuild any downstream from scratch. Stream processing with Apache Flink (the industry leader for stateful stream processing — exactly-once, event-time windows, savepoints for upgrades, used by Alibaba at 4 billion events/sec), Kafka Streams (simpler, no separate cluster — a library embedded in your app, but limited to Kafka-to-Kafka processing), or Apache Spark Structured Streaming (batch-oriented semantics applied to streams, higher latency but familiar API for data engineers). At this scale, build an internal event platform with self-service topic provisioning, an event catalog (searchable registry of all event types, schemas, producers, and consumers), and automated compliance checks (PII detection in event payloads, retention enforcement).",tools:["Kafka (self-managed clusters)","Confluent Cloud","AWS Kinesis","Apache Flink","Apache Spark Structured Streaming","custom event platform"]}
     },
     
     levelUp:[
       {from:"small",to:"medium",trigger:">1K background jobs/day, or job failures are causing permanent data loss because Redis restarts lose in-flight jobs, or you need cross-service communication (Service A needs to tell Service B to do something)",
        action:"Move to a dedicated, persistent message queue. If on AWS: start with SQS — create a queue, configure a DLQ (set maxReceiveCount to 3), and replace your Sidekiq enqueue with an SQS SendMessage call. Your consumer becomes a separate process that long-polls the queue. Implementation: (1) Define the message schema in a shared Protobuf or JSON Schema file. (2) Generate the unique message_id on the producer side (UUID v4). (3) Build the consumer loop: poll → deserialize → check idempotency (Redis SETNX on message_id with 24h TTL) → process → delete message. (4) Set visibility_timeout to 2× your max expected processing time. (5) Monitor: CloudWatch alarm on ApproximateNumberOfMessagesVisible (queue depth) and ApproximateAgeOfOldestMessage (consumer lag). (6) Build a DLQ inspection script on day one — print each DLQ message in human-readable format with failure reason. You WILL need it within the first week."},
       
       {from:"medium",to:"large",trigger:">100K messages/day, or you need ordering guarantees per entity (all events for order #123 processed in sequence), or 3+ independent systems need to consume the same events, or you need replay (rebuild a search index, re-process historical data for a new analytics model)",
        action:"Introduce Kafka (or Kafka-compatible: Redpanda, MSK). Start with AWS MSK for managed operations or Confluent Cloud for fully managed. Implementation: (1) Create your first topic: 'order-events' with 6 partitions (allows up to 6 parallel consumers), replication factor 3, 7-day retention. (2) Partition key = entity ID (order_id) — this ensures all events for one order land in the same partition and are processed in order. (3) Install Confluent Schema Registry (free, open-source). Define your event schemas in Avro or Protobuf. Set compatibility to BACKWARD. Register schemas before producing. (4) Produce events with the Kafka producer (enable.idempotence=true to prevent duplicate production on retries). (5) Create consumer groups: 'search-indexer' (reads order events and updates Elasticsearch), 'analytics-pipeline' (reads and writes to data warehouse), 'notification-sender' (reads and sends push notifications). Each group independently tracks its offset. (6) Add Burrow (open-source by LinkedIn) or use CloudWatch consumer group lag metrics (MSK) for monitoring consumer lag. Alert when lag exceeds 5 minutes of event age. (7) Set up a DLQ topic: when a consumer can't process a message after 3 retries, produce it to 'order-events-dlq' with the error message attached. Build a DLQ dashboard."},
       
       {from:"large",to:"hyper",trigger:">1M events/sec, or event sourcing is a business requirement (audit trail, temporal queries, full system rebuild from events), or you need global fan-out across multiple datacenters",
        action:"Scale to a multi-cluster, multi-datacenter event streaming platform. Implementation: (1) Deploy Kafka clusters per domain: 'payments-kafka' (3 brokers), 'user-events-kafka' (5 brokers), 'analytics-kafka' (10 brokers). Separate clusters contain blast radius — an operational issue in the analytics cluster doesn't affect payment processing. (2) Set up MirrorMaker 2 (open-source) or Confluent Cluster Linking for cross-datacenter replication of critical topics. Active-active: both DCs produce to local cluster, MM2 replicates bidirectionally. Use a prefixed topic naming convention (dc1.order-events, dc2.order-events) and a consumer that reads from both. (3) Implement stream processing with Apache Flink: deploy a Flink cluster (Kubernetes-based via Flink Operator), write stateful processing jobs in Java/Python, use event-time windows for accurate aggregations (handles late-arriving events). Enable checkpointing every 30 seconds for fault tolerance. (4) Build an internal event platform portal: teams self-service topic creation through a UI that enforces naming conventions, minimum partition count, replication factor, schema registration, and PII classification. (5) Establish an event catalog: every event type has an owner team, a human-readable description, a registered schema, a list of known producers and consumers, and SLO targets for production latency and consumer lag. This prevents the 'nobody knows what topic X does' problem. (6) Introduce retention policies per topic classification: 'operational' = 7 days, 'event-sourced' = forever (compacted), 'telemetry' = 24 hours. Monitor storage growth and set alerts for clusters approaching 80% disk."}
     ],
     children:[]}
  ]
};
